    ["lat-lon"]
    .str.split(",", expand=True)[0]
    .astype(float)
    .head()
)
📊 The values look the same but are now proper decimal numbers.

Python no longer displays quote marks around them — that is the visual cue that the dtype changed from object to float64. You can now:

Compute mean(), std(), min(), max() — all arithmetic works.
Plot them on a map — geographic libraries expect float coordinates.
Compare them with >, <, == — boolean comparisons work correctly.
We apply the exact same .str.split(...)[1].astype(float) pattern to longitude, which lives at index [1].

